0.body: Welcome in discord.py-by-example! This book is a collection of examples of how to use the discord.py library. It is meant to be used as a reference book, so you can read the chapters in any order you want. However, I recommend you to read the chapters in the order they are presented, as some chapters may require knowledge from previous chapters. If you want to contribute to this book, you can do so by creating a pull request on The GitHub repository of this book. You can also create an issue if you find a mistake or if you want to suggest a new chapter. If you have any question, you can DM me at @AliBen#7502 on Discord or create an issue on the GitHub repository of this book.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: The first step in the bot creation is to configure the bot. First we need to create a new application in developer portal. To do that, go to https://discord.com/developers/applications and click on "New Application". Then, you need to give a name to your application and click on "Create". Now, you can see the dashboard of your application. In this dashboard, you can see the client ID of your application, the client secret and the bot token. The bot token is the most important thing here. This token is used to connect your bot to Discord. Never share this token with anyone . If someone has this token, he can do anything with your bot. If you think that someone has your token, you can regenerate it by clicking on "Regenerate" in the bot section of the dashboard. Once you have your bot token, you can invite your bot to your server. To do that, go to the OAuth2 section of the dashboard. In the "Scopes" section, select "bot". Then, in the "Bot Permissions" section, select the permissions that your bot will need. For example, if you want to create a bot that will send messages, you need to select the "Send Messages" permission. Once you have selected the permissions, you can copy the link in the "Scopes" section and paste it in your browser. Then, you can select the server where you want to invite your bot and click on "Continue". Finally, click on "Authorize" to invite your bot to your server. Now we need to download the discord.py library. To do that, open a terminal and type pip install discord.py. Once the library is installed, we can start coding our bot.
1.title: Bot Configuration

10.body: Commands are the main reason why we use discord.py . They are the main way to interact with the bot. In this chapter, we will learn how to create commands, how to use them based on their parameters, and how to handle errors.
10.title: Commands

11.body:
To create a new commande we need to create a function with the decorator bot_name.command() where bot_name is the name of the bot. Each command will have the following structure: @bot_name.command()
async def command_name(ctx : commands.Context, arg1, arg2, ...): # Code The first argument of this command is the context of the command. This argument is mandatory and need to be named ctx as convention. This argument is of type commands.Contextand it contains all the information about the command. For others arguments, you can add as many as you want, there are just some rules to follow with strings that will be explained later. For example, if we want to create a command that will send "Hello, World!" when a user sends "!hello", we can do this: @bot.command()
async def hello(ctx : commands.Context): await ctx.send("Hello, World!") To call this command, we need to send "!hello" (If the current prefix is "!" else change this with your prefix) in a channel where the bot can see. So the final code will be: >>> !hello
Hello, World!
11.breadcrumbs: Commands » Creating a Command » Creating a Command
11.title: Creating a Command

12.body:
To create a command with an unique argument, we need to add an argument to the function. This argument can be of any type. For example if we want to create a command that takes an integer n as argument and send the number from 1 to n, we can do this: @bot.command()
async def count(ctx : commands.Context, n : int): for i in range(1, n + 1): await ctx.send(i) To call this command, we need to send "!count 10" (If the current prefix is "!" else change this with your prefix) in a channel where the bot can see. This will send the numbers from 1 to 10 in the channel where the command was sent. If we send "!count 5", this will send the numbers from 1 to 5 in the channel where the command was sent, etc... If we send "!count 10.5", this will raise an error because the argument n is of type int and "10.5" is not an integer. If we send "!count abc", this will also raise an error because "abc" is not an integer. This is because discord.py use a system named converters to convert the arguments to the right type. We will see this later. (See basic converters )
12.breadcrumbs: Commands » Single argument commands » Single argument commands
12.title: Single argument commands

13.body:
To create commands with multiple arguments, we need to add arguments to the function. These arguments can be of any type except string. String are a special case and will be explained later. For example, if we want to create a command that takes two integers a and b as arguments and send the sum of a and b, we can do this: @bot.command()
async def add(ctx : commands.Context, a : int, b : int): await ctx.send(a + b) To call this command, we need to send "!add 5 10" (If the current prefix is "!" else change this with your prefix) in a channel where the bot can see. This will send "15" in the channel where the command was sent. If we send "!add 10 20", this will send "30" in the channel where the command was sent, etc... So the final code will be: >>> !add 5 10
15
>>> !add 10 20
30
>>> !add "Hello" "World"
Command raised an exception: BadArgument: Converting to "int" failed for parameter "a".
13.breadcrumbs: Commands » Multiple argument commands » Multiple argument commands
13.title: Multiple argument commands

14.body:
When we want to create a command that takes a string as an argument it do not work as expected. The naive implementation of a command that takes a string as an argument can be : @bot.command()
async def echo(ctx : commands.Context, message : str): await ctx.send(message) But if we call this command with "!echo Hello World", this will only send "Hello" in the channel where the command was sent. This is because discord.py take each word as an argument. So "Hello World" is seen as two arguments: "Hello" and "World". To fix this, we need to use the * operator named keyword-only argument . This operator will take all the remaining arguments as a single argument. So if we use this operator, the command will be: @bot.command()
async def echo(ctx : commands.Context, *, message : str): await ctx.send(message) Now if we call this command with "!echo Hello World", this will send "Hello World" in the channel where the command was sent. This is because the * operator take all the remaining arguments as a single argument. So "Hello World" is seen as a single argument. One thing to notice is that we can not add an argument after the string one because the * operator take all the remaining arguments as a single argument. So all others arguments need to be set before the * operator. For example if we want to create a command that takes a string as an argument and a number as an argument, we can do this: @bot.command()
async def echo(ctx : commands.Context, n : int, *, message : str): for i in range(n): await ctx.send(message) If we call this command with "!echo 3 Hello World", this will send "Hello World" 3 times in the channel where the command was sent. So the final code will be: >>> !echo 3 Hello World
Hello World
Hello World
Hello World
14.breadcrumbs: Commands » String argument in commands » String argument in commands
14.title: String argument in commands

15.body:
discord.py let us create commands that takes a variable number of arguments. To do this, we need to use the *args argument in our command. This argument will take all the remaining arguments as a list. So if we use this argument, the command will be: @bot.command()
async def sum(ctx : commands.Context, *args : int): await ctx.send(sum(args)) Now if we call this command with "!sum 1 2 3 4 5", this will send "15" in the channel where the command was sent. This is because the *args argument take all the remaining arguments as a list. So "1 2 3 4 5" is seen as a list of 5 elements: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5].
15.breadcrumbs: Commands » Unlimited arguments in commands » Unlimited arguments in commands
15.title: Unlimited arguments in commands

16.body:
Here is an example command : @bot.command(name='welcome') async def welcome_command(ctx : commands.Context, member : discord.Member, n : int) -> None: for _ in range(n): await ctx.send(f'Hello {member.mention}, welcome to guild {ctx.guild.name}, how are you ?') This command is named "welcome" and take two arguments: a member and a number. This command will send "Hello {member.mention}, welcome to guild {ctx.guild.name}, how are you ?" n times in the channel where the command was sent. For example if we call this command with "!welcome @user 3", this will send "Hello @user, welcome to guild My Guild, how are you ?" 3 times in the channel where the command was sent. This commands seems to work but we can have a lot of problems with it. For example, the command can be called outside of a guild, the member may not exists or the number may not be an integer or may be negative. To fix this, we need to add some error handling. To handle errors in discord.py we need to use the @command_name.error decorator. This decorator will be called if an error occurs in the command. This decorator take a function as an argument. This function will be called if an error occurs in the command. This function need to take two arguments: the first one is the context of the command and the second one is the error that occurred and it need to be async. We can name it as we want but it is recommended to name it on_command_name_error where "command_name" is the name of the command. For example, if we want to handle errors in the "welcome" command, we can do this: @welcome_command.error
async def on_welcome_command_error(ctx : commands.Context, error : commands.CommandError) -> None: pass But first we need to raise some errors directly in the command. We need to check if the command is called outside of a guild, if the member exists and if the number is an integer and is positive. To do this, we can use the ext.commands module. This module contains all the errors that can be raised in a command. For example, if we want to check if the command is called outside of a guild and if the number is correct, we can do this: @bot.command(name='new_welcome')
async def new_welcome_command(ctx : commands.Context, member : discord.Member, n : int) -> None: if ctx.guild is None: raise commands.GuildNotFound('This command can only be used in a guild') if n < 0 or not isinstance(n, int): raise commands.BadArgument for _ in range(n): await ctx.send(f'Hello {member.mention}, welcome to guild {ctx.guild.name}, how are you ?') And now to handle these errors, we can do this: @new_welcome_command.error
async def on_new_welcome_command_error(ctx : commands.Context, error : commands.CommandError): if isinstance(error, commands.GuildNotFound): return await ctx.send('This command can only be used in a guild') elif isinstance(error, commands.MissingRequiredArgument): return await ctx.send('You need to specify a member and a number') elif isinstance(error, commands.BadArgument): return await ctx.send('There is a problem with the arguments') elif isinstance(error, commands.MemberNotFound): return await ctx.send('The member was not found') # If the error is not handled, we need to raise it otherwise the error will be ignored raise error Now if we call this command with "!new_welcome @user 3", this will send "Hello @user, welcome to guild My Guild, how are you ?" 3 times in the channel where the command was sent. But if we call this command with "!new_welcome @user -3", this will send "There is a problem with the arguments" in the channel where the command was sent. And if we call this command with "!new_welcome", this will send "You need to specify a member and a number" in the channel where the command was sent.
16.breadcrumbs: Commands » Commands error handling » Commands error handling
16.title: Commands error handling

17.body: In Python we do not really need to specify the type of a variable. We can just do a = 1 and Python will know that a is an integer. However, in some cases, we need to specify the type of a variable. For example, when we are creating a function that takes a parameter, we need to specify the type of that parameter. This is called type hinting . For example, if we want to create a function that takes an integer as a parameter, we can do: def add(a : int): return a + 1 In this example, we are creating a function that takes an integer a as a parameter and return a + 1. This is called type hinting . This is useful for the developer to know what type of data the function takes as a parameter. However, this is not useful for the user of the function. But in native Python this is only used for documentation. However, in discord.py, this is used to convert the user input to the type specified in the function. This is called converters . In this chapter, we will see how to use the native Python type hinting to create converters.
17.title: Converters

18.body:
Sometimes we just want to accept one type for a parameter. In Python, we can use the typing module to specify the type of a parameter but it is just used for type hinting and does not actually restrict the type of the parameter. In discord.py there are converters that can be used to restrict the type of a parameter. For example, if we want to add two numbers like : @bot.command()
async def add(ctx : commands.Context, a : int, b : int): await ctx.send(a + b) We can see the usage of the int converter. When we will call this commands all the parameters will be converted to int before being passed to the function. If we pass a string that cannot be converted to an int, the command will not be called and an error will be raised. This notation work for all the native types in Python.
18.title: Basic Converter

19.body: When our bot start to get bigger, we will need to split our code into multiple classes. To do that, we will need to create a new class that will inherit from commands.Cog. In this class, we will load all the commands that we want to use in the setup function. This is used to better organize the code and group related functionality together.
19.title: Cogs

2.breadcrumbs: Bot Configuration » First Bot » First Bot
2.title: First Bot

20.body:
When our bot start to get bigger, we will need to split our code into multiple Cogs and to do that, we will need to create a new class that will inherit from commands.Bot. In this class, we will load all the Cogs that we want to use in the setup_hook function. import discord
from discord.ext import commands class MyBot(commands.Bot): def __init__(self): super().__init__( command_prefix='!', intents=discord.Intents.all() ) async def setup_hook(self) -> None: # Method called before the `on_ready` event # This line setup all the slash commands await self.tree.sync() async def on_ready(self): print('-------------') print(f'Logged in as {self.user}') print(f'Bot is ready.') bot = MyBot()
bot.run('token')
20.breadcrumbs: Cogs » Advanced Bot Setup » Advanced Bot Setup
20.title: Advanced Bot Setup

21.body:
In the discord.py library, there is a concept called Cog . A Cog is a class that contains a set of commands and listeners . They are used to better organize the code and group related functionality together. Each Cog is created by inheriting from the commands.Cog class, so a Cog has the following structure: import discord
from discord.ext import commands class CogName(commands.Cog): def __init__(self) -> None: ... Generally, a parameter is added to the class's initialization which is the bot , in order to directly use its functionality within the Cog . This gives us a complete syntax for a Cog: import discord
from discord.ext import commands class CogName(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot: commands.Bot) -> None: self.bot = bot
21.breadcrumbs: Cogs » How Cogs Work » How Cogs Work
21.title: How Cogs Work

22.body: To add a new command to a Cog , we will use the @commands.command decorator. In addition to the context , our command should take self as a parameter, like all commands within a class . So, it would be: class ExampleCog(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot: commands.Bot) -> None: self.bot = bot @commands.command() async def command_name(self, ctx: commands.Context, param1, ..., paramN): ... Let's create a echo command that takes a string parameter and returns the same string. Here's an example: class ExampleCog(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot: commands.Bot) -> None: self.bot = bot @commands.command(name="echo") async def echo_message(self, ctx: commands.Context, *, message: str) -> discord.Message: return await ctx.send(message)
22.breadcrumbs: Cogs » Commands in Cogs » Commands in Cogs
22.title: Commands in Cogs

23.body: To create a new event (named listeners in Cogs), we will need to create a new function that will have the @commands.Cog.listener() decorator. This function will take a function as an argument. This function will be called when the event is triggered. For example, if we want to create a listener that will be called when a message is sent, we can do this: class MyCog(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot : commands.Bot): self.bot = bot @commands.Cog.listener() async def on_message(self, message : discord.Message): print(f'{message.author} sent a message.') Now if we send a message in a channel where the bot can see, this will print the name of the author of the message in the console. But we can also set the name of the listener with the name argument of the decorator. For example, if we want to create a listener that will be called when a message is sent, we can do this: class MyCog(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot : commands.Bot): self.bot = bot @commands.Cog.listener(name='on_message') async def my_listener(self, message : discord.Message): print(f'{message.author} sent a message.')
23.breadcrumbs: Cogs » Events in Cogs » Events in Cogs
23.title: Events in Cogs

24.body: Embeds are a concept in Discord that allows us to send rich content in our messages. They are used to make our messages more appealing and to provide more information to the user. In this chapter, we will learn how to use embeds in our bots and how to customize them.
24.title: Embeds

25.body: In the discord.py library, an embed is an object that allows displaying messages with more content and, most importantly, more visually appealing. An Embed uses the discord.Embed object, which takes three main optional arguments : color represents the color that our embed will have once sent - this argument must take an object of type discord.Color. title represents the title of our embed and is of type string . description is also a string and represents the description that will be displayed once sent. In addition to that, each embed has a list of methods that allow adding additional elements => [[How to modify an embed in the discord.py library]].
25.breadcrumbs: Embeds » How Embeds Work » How Embeds Work
25.title: How Embeds Work

26.body:
An example of creating an Embed could be: embed = discord.Embed( title="I am a title!", description="I am the description", color=discord.Color.green()
) Once created, you can send it using the method ctx.send(embed=embed).
26.title: Examples

28.body:
In the discord.py library, there are several types of commands . The simplest ones are the regular commands that are used with a predefined prefix . However, there is another type of command called slash commands . These commands are not called with a developer-defined prefix but with /, which triggers a menu where all our slash commands are listed. These commands are extremely convenient because they are natively supported by Discord and provide a much more user-friendly interface. That's why it is recommended to use them instead of regular commands. Additionally, when calling a slash command , its parameters have predefined types , which helps avoid many errors, and their functioning eliminates the issue of string parsing . To create a slash command , there are two ways: the first one is to use the @bot.tree.command() decorator, which is a method of the command_tree that handles all the slash commands . Another way to do it is by importing the discord.app_commands module and using the app_commands.command() decorator, which functions exactly the same as in the first case. A slash command will have one of the following structures: from discord import app_commands @bot.tree.command()
async def test_command(interaction: discord.Interaction): await interaction.response.send_message("test") # or @app_commands.command()
async def test_command(interaction: discord.Interaction): await interaction.response.send_message("test") As we can see, there are some differences compared to regular commands . The two differences we see here are: Replacing commands.Context with discord.Interaction. Slash commands do not use a context but an interaction . The functioning of an Interaction is somewhat similar, excluding the details, but the parameters used to accomplish the same tasks are different. Instead of using ctx.send() to send a message, we use interaction.response.send_message(). Its functioning is the same, with the only difference being that it can only be used once.
28.title: Slash Commands

3.body:
To run the bot we need to use the run method of the commands.Bot class. This method takes one mandatory argument: token. This is the token of the bot that we want to run. We can get this token from the Discord Developer Portal . For more information about the loading state of the bot we will create a new event on_ready (see on_ready event ). import discord
from discord.ext import commands bot = commands.Bot(command_prefix="!", intents=discord.Intents(messages=True)) @bot.event
async def on_ready(): print("Bot is ready") bot.run("token") # Replace token with your bot's token For more security, we can store the token in a file called .env and load it using the dotenv module.
3.breadcrumbs: Bot Configuration » First Bot » Running the Bot
3.title: Running the Bot

30.body:
In the previous chapter, we learned how to create slash commands in a bot that is not structured in cogs . However, if we want to use slash commands in a bot that is structured in cogs , we will have to use a different approach. In this chapter, we will learn how to create slash commands in a bot that is structured in cogs . To create a slash command in a bot that is structured in cogs , we will have to use the app_commands.command() decorator. This decorator is used to create slash commands and is imported from the discord.app_commands module. The app_commands.command() decorator is used in the same way as the bot.tree.command() decorator, but it is used in a cog instead of a bot . So an example of a slash command in a cog would be: from discord.ext import commands
from discord import app_commands class SlashCommands(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot): self.bot = bot @app_commands.command() async def test_command(self, interaction: discord.Interaction): await interaction.response.send_message("test") As we can see, the only difference between a slash command in a bot and a slash command in a cog is the decorator used to create it. However, there is one more thing we need to do to make our slash commands work.
30.breadcrumbs: Slash Commands » Slash Commands in Cogs » Slash Commands in Cogs
30.title: Slash Commands in Cogs

31.body:
Sometimes we want to have a command that can be used both as a regular command and as a slash command . This is possible thanks to the hybrid_command() decorator, which is imported from the discord.ext.commands module. With this decorator we do not have the Interaction object, so we will have to use the context object. An example of a hybrid command would be: from discord.ext import commands @commands.hybrid_command()
async def test_command(self, ctx: commands.Context): await ctx.send("test") As we can see, the only difference between a regular command and a hybrid command is the decorator used to create it. Now to call this command we just have to use the prefix or the slash command.
31.title: Hybrid Commands

33.body: To create a hybrid command in a bot that is structured in cogs , we will have to use the hybrid_command() decorator. This decorator is used to create hybrid commands and is imported from the discord.ext.commands module. The hybrid_command() decorator is used in the same way as the bot.command() decorator, but it is used in a cog instead of a bot . So an example of a hybrid command in a cog would be: from discord.ext import commands class HybridCommands(commands.Cog): def __init__(self, bot): self.bot = bot @commands.hybrid_command() async def test_command(self, ctx: commands.Context): await ctx.send("test") So as we can see it works the same way as a hybrid command in a bot .

34.body: As we saw in the chapter 3 about basic converters , we can use the native Python type hinting to create converters. However, this is not the only way to create converters. In this chapter, we will see how to create converters using functions, and how to create advanced converters. We will also see how to use the converters provided by discord.py.
34.title: Converters

35.body:
We saw in the chapter 3 that we can use Type Hints to convert the arguments of a command to the type we want. However, sometimes we want to convert the arguments of a command to a type that is not supported by Type Hints . For example, we may want to convert the arguments of a command to a function . This is possible thanks to functions converters. Let's take this command as an example: @bot.command()
async def up(ctx : commands.Context, *, content : str) -> discord.Message: await ctx.send(content.upper()) This command takes a string as an argument and sends it back in uppercase. However, we may want to convert the argument to a function instead of a string. We will create a new function that takes a string as an argument and returns it in uppercase. def to_uppercase(string : str) -> str: return string.upper() And now instead of the str type hint, we will use the to_uppercase function. @bot.command()
async def up(ctx : commands.Context, *, content : to_uppercase) -> discord.Message: await ctx.send(content) Now when we call the command, the argument will be converted to a function instead of a string. If we call the command with the argument test, the bot will send TEST. >>> !up test
TEST
35.title: Function Converter

36.body:
If we want some more advanced Converters it is possible to create custom converters class that inherit from discord.ext.commands.Converter or another subclass of discord.ext.commands.Converter. For example, we can create a converter that converts the argument to a discord.Member object. To do this we will create a class that inherits from discord.ext.commands.Converter and we will override the convert() method. This method takes two arguments: ctx and argument. The ctx argument is the context object and the argument argument is the argument to convert. This method must return the converted argument. So our converter will look like this: from discord.ext import commands class MemberConverter(commands.Converter): async def convert(self, ctx: commands.Context, argument: str) -> discord.Member: return discord.utils.get(ctx.guild.members, name=argument) To use this converter we will have to pass it as a type hint to the argument we want to convert. @bot.command()
async def test(ctx: commands.Context, member: MemberConverter): await ctx.send(member.name) Now when we call the command with the name of a member as an argument, the argument will be converted to a discord.Member object. >>> !test @member
member
36.title: Advanced Converter

37.body:
Some of the decorators are so commonly used that they have been included in the discord.py library. These decorators are called discord converters and they are used to convert the arguments of a command into a specific type. We already saw some of them like discord.Member or discord.Role. To use them we will have to pass them as a type hint to the argument we want to convert. For example, if we want to convert the argument to a discord.Member object, we will have to pass discord.Member as a type hint to the argument. @bot.command()
async def test(ctx: commands.Context, member: discord.Member): await ctx.send(member.name) Now when we call the command with the name of a member as an argument, the argument will be converted to a discord.Member object. >>> !test @member

37.title: Discord Converters

4.body: Events are a key concept in the discord.py library. They are used to detect when something happens in the Discord server, such as a new message being sent or a member joining the server. In this chapter, we will learn how to use events in our bots.
4.title: Events

5.breadcrumbs: Events » How Events Work » How Events Work
5.title: How Events Work

6.body:
An event is a type of function that triggers every time a specific action is performed. The behavior of this function will depend on the event that is created. For example, there is an event that triggers as soon as the Bot is started or another event that triggers with every new message. The structure of an event is as follows: @bot_name.event
async def event_name(param1, ..., paramN): ... In this example, bot_name represents the name of the variable containing the commands.Bot object. The event method of this class is called as a decorator to convert the following function into an event. The name of the event is represented by event_name, which will be different for each created event. The function's parameters are specific to each created event (to know all the events, refer to the documentation). In summary, events are very useful for managing Discord-specific actions that are outside the control of the bot. You can find all events here .
6.breadcrumbs: Events » How Events Work » What are events?
6.title: What are events?

7.body:
To use an event, we need to create a function with the bot_name.event decorator. For example, if we want to use the on_ready event, we need to create a function with the bot_name.event decorator and pass the on_ready event as an argument. This function will be called when the on_ready event is called. For example, if we want to print a message when the on_ready event is called, we can do this: @bot.event
async def on_ready(): print("Bot is ready") Now each time the bot load we will have the following output: >>> Bot is ready
7.breadcrumbs: Events » How Events Work » How to use events
7.title: How to use events

8.body:
The on_ready event is called when the bot is online and ready to receive events. This event is called only once, when the bot is ready. This event takes no arguments and need to be created like this: @bot.event
async def on_ready(): print("Bot is ready") In this example, we are printing a message when the on_ready event is called. So every time the bot is ready, the message Bot is ready will be printed in the console. So if we run the bot, we will have the following output: >>> Bot is ready This event is very useful for knowing when the bot is ready to receive events but useless for all other cases.
8.title: on_ready event

9.body:
The on_message event is called when a message is sent in a channel that the bot can see. This event takes a message of type discord.Message as an argument and need to be created like this: @bot.event
async def on_message(message : discord.Message): print(message.content) With this event we can for example create a command that will send a message when a user sends a specific message. For example, if we want to send "Hello!" when a user sends "Hi", we can do this: @bot.event
async def on_message(message : discord.Message): if message.author.bot: return if message.content == "Hi": await message.channel.send("Hello!") In this example, we are checking if the message is sent by a bot. If it is, we return (This is used to avoid the bot to reply to itself and creating an infinite loop). Then we are checking if the message content is "Hi". If it is, we are sending "Hello!" in the channel where the message was sent. To check if the message content is "Hi", we are using the content attribute of the discord.Message class. This attribute returns the content of the message as a string. To send a message in a channel, we are using the send method of the discord.TextChannel class. This method takes one mandatory argument: content. This is the content of the message that will be sent. This method returns a discord.Message object that represents the message that was sent. We are using the await keyword before the send method because this method is a coroutine. For more information about coroutines, see this .
9.title: on_message event
